His words were not intended to be interpreted as an olive branch to Taiwan, a democratic island that Beijing has long claimed as its own, but as a statement of friendship with the United States, the democratically elected Taiwanese government and all democracies in the world.
But Xi Jinping has his eyes on Taiwan, and he is not afraid to make the point in a way that cannot be interpreted otherwise. “I want to make one thing clear. Taiwan is China’s sacred territory. Anyone who tries to split Taiwan from China is making a big mistake,” he said in his speech, which was later shared on his official website. He continued, “The Chinese government will never allow anyone to separate Taiwan from China.”

We have an opportunity to re-think health technology labeling to rebuild trust and help people make better choices.

However, the FDA did not require a nutrition label to accompany this drug. A nutrition label would have alerted consumers that the drug has serious and potentially dangerous side effects.

Guterres also urged him to work with the new Parliament to address the “growing political and economic crisis.” 
Milei has faced controversy in his career. He was once imprisoned for allegedly inciting riots, and he later led a protest march with a group called the “Free the People March.”

In 2023, Climate change is already negatively affecting inequality and poverty. The extent to which this happens at the micro-level remains relatively unexplored. This is particularly relevant in low- or middle-income countries. However, in such countries, access to the formal labour market is limited. As such, micro-level research has mostly focused on self-employed and household workers in developing countries.
This book presents an extensive overview of the most important issues regarding climate change and inequality. The focus lies on how climate change impacts income and assets and, as a result, living conditions. The book includes chapters from leading scholars, who analyse the impact of climate change on income inequality at the global level and for the four major climate change regions (the Northern, Southern, Eastern and Western hemispheres). A special section is dedicated to research on how climate change affects inequality within countries. The book further discusses the role of the climate change-affected populations in the debate on climate change. Lastly, the authors explore the role of climate change in the context of climate justice.
This book will be of interest to all scholars interested in climate change and inequality, with a focus on income and assets.

In 2023, The 1973 october war, the devastating invasion that arab armies launched precisely 50 years earlier, plus a day. It was the last time israelis awoke to a life-changing assault that its intelligence apparatus had not seen coming. Another analogue might be the tet offensive, the 1968 viet cong surprise attack that changed the course of the vietnam war. But this analogy may miss something important: in the years since 1973, israelis have had to face a very different threat. They’ve had to deal with a nuclear armenia. They’ve had to fight Hezbollah. They’ve had to fight isis, islamists, and al-qaeda.
Now, for the first time, israel is facing a massive and coordinated multi-front war with iranian-backed proxy armies on its northern, eastern, and southern borders. A new kind of threat is challenging the old way of doing things. And the old way of doing things is no longer working. The same old tactics are proving ineffective against this new enemy. That’s why, on february 20th, israel launched what many are calling a game-changing strike against the nuclear program of iran.

What is an Electrocardiogram (ECG)?
An electrocardiogram is a non-invasive test that allows doctors to detect the heart’s electrical activity. This test is commonly used to diagnose various heart conditions, such as arrhythmias, heart attacks, and heart failure. It’s important to note that while ECGs can be a helpful tool, they aren’t a replacement for a medical professional’s diagnosis.
How Does an ECG Work?

It’s part of the EU’s Digital Services Act (DSA) that requires digital service providers to protect users under 18 years old.
Meta and Snap will need to provide additional details to the European Commission, the bloc’s executive arm, and will be asked to present a plan of action. This new deadline comes after the companies failed to meet the earlier deadline set by the EU in 2022.
According to EU law, the companies must protect users under 18 from harmful content that includes child abuse, child pornography, and content promoting or inciting violence. The companies need to show they have taken measures to prevent such content from being posted on their platforms and have adequate systems to remove it when it is flagged. They must also have processes in place to protect minors who have been harmed by such content.
Facebook and Instagram owner Meta said it had already been cooperating with the EU and was looking forward to continuing to work together to protect children online.

In 2023, Virtual pipeline systems industry was estimated to be worth US$ 1.4 billion by 2022. A CAGR of 6.2% is projected from 2023 to 2031. The prevalence of small-scale LNG projects is increasing, often accompanied by virtual pipeline systems. The rising number of such projects is expected to boost the virtual pipeline systems market.
A Virtual Pipeline System (VPS) is a network of LNG (Liquefied Natural Gas) storage and transfer facilities, interconnected by virtual pipelines, for transporting natural gas over long distances. The VPS operates similarly to an interstate pipeline system but lacks the physical infrastructure required to transport the gas. Instead, the gas is stored and transferred virtually through a series of interconnections, making it a more flexible and efficient solution for transporting LNG. VPS has gained popularity in recent years as a cost-effective alternative to traditional LNG projects. It is particularly well-suited for countries with large oil and gas reserves but limited infrastructure to transport and distribute gas.

In 2023,  slow-slip events (sses) are slow earthquake ruptures that generate just a few centimeters of slip over periods ranging from days to years. They are thought to occur in many of the world's subduction zones, but these subtle slips can be tricky to observe. To understand sses and other small earthquakes, scientists in the U.S. and Japan have developed a way to calculate the stress buildup leading up to an ss event. This study  shows that ss events occur when the stress in the fault is just 30 to 50 percent of the strength of the fault material. The findings could improve predictions of ss and other small earthquakes and aid tsunami warnings.

In 2023, Australian batsman Dean Jones suffered from severe dehydration during the tied Test against India at the Chepauk in Chennai. Jones replied, "What are you talking about? I am up to the job." He went on to play 105 Test matches, scoring 8,832 runs and hitting 23 centuries.
Jones scored a half-century on debut against the West Indies at Melbourne in 1984, but did not get a Test ton until six years later against New Zealand at Wellington. He scored 210 there, making him the sixth Australian to score a double hundred on debut.

In 2023, Israel is considering hiring Tony Blair as humanitarian coordinator for Gaza. Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu reportedly hopes Blair's experience will lend legitimacy to Israel's military campaign. Blair served as envoy to Israel and Palestine for the Middle East Quartet. The Quartet was a grouping of international organizations and representatives that included the UN and the EU. It was formed in 2002. The Quartet's stated mission was to support the creation of a Palestinian state, a process that has yet to be achieved. The Quartet was a non-binding framework and had no enforcement power. However, the Quartet's recommendations were widely regarded as legitimate and influential. Blair was appointed Quartet envoy in 2007, and was tasked with facilitating Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations. These negotiations were held in Annapolis, Maryland, and were attended by Blair. They were not successful, and the Quartet was dissolved in 2011. Blair served as Quartet envoy for 2.5 years. He was succeeded by Robert Serry, the UN special coordinator for the Middle East peace process. Blair's role as Quartet envoy was to promote peace between Israel and Palestine. Blair was widely respected and viewed as a legitimate actor in Middle East peace efforts

The Kurdish People's Protection Units (YPG), the militia that forms the backbone of the U.S.-led Syrian Democratic Forces, is an affiliate of the PKK. 
Turkey views the PKK as a terrorist group and is fighting it in northern Syria. 
"We cannot have any doubt about the determination of Sweden to take the necessary steps to eradicate the PKK's terror organization and its activities," Oktay said, adding that the country has not yet lifted a ban on the outlawed Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) and its affiliates.
"The commission will review the issue further and the necessary steps will be taken," he said.

In 2023, Sosei Group Corporation is in discussions with GSK to regain full ownership of GSK4381406. The oral GPR35 agonist is in development as a potential new treatment for Inflammatory Bowel Diseases (IBD) and is now owned by GSK. In return, GSK will receive an upfront payment, further milestones and royalties.
Sosei Heptares’ proprietary GPCR (G protein-coupled receptor) drug discovery platform has been applied to identify small molecule agonists for GPR35, a receptor which regulates gut inflammation. GSK4381406 has now entered a Phase 2b trial in patients with moderate-to-severe Crohn’s disease and has the potential to become the first orally active treatment for the disease.
In the absence of disease-modifying treatments for IBD, currently available therapies focus on alleviating symptoms. New treatments are therefore urgently needed to treat the underlying condition and avoid the progression of disease.
Sosei Heptares has a portfolio of seven GPCR drug candidates, which are at various stages of development in a broad range of therapeutic areas.

In 2023, Researchers have detected buried under the continent's ice sheet a vast ancient landscape. The landscape, replete with valleys and ridges, apparently shaped by rivers before being engulfed by glaciation. It is possible that the landscape's creation occurred between 1.2 and 1.6 million years ago, as indicated by the radiocarbon dating of the boulders found in the valley bottoms. This discovery offers a glimpse into the complex interplay between ice and landforms that has shaped the Earth's surface throughout the Ice Age. The findings, published in the journal Geophysical Research Letters, provide a valuable addition to the growing understanding of this crucial period in Earth's history. 
A team of researchers, led by Dr. Thomas Steffensen from the Geological Survey of Denmark and Greenland, utilized a suite of cutting-edge technology to uncover the hidden landscape beneath the ice sheet. The researchers used ground-penetrating radar to generate high-resolution images of the subglacial landscape. These images were then combined with data from previous seismic studies to produce a comprehensive picture of the area. This integrated approach allowed the researchers to overcome the challenges posed by the thick ice sheet and complex terrain.

In 2023, Astrophysicists have made a direct observation of atomic oxygen on Venus’ dayside. About 96% of the atmosphere on the second planet from the Sun is made up of carbon dioxide, a smidge of other gasses including nitrogen, and practically no oxygen. The atmosphere is so thick that astronomers were previously unable to directly observe the presence of atomic oxygen in Venus’ upper atmosphere.
However, thanks to a European Space Agency-led spacecraft called Venus Express, scientists were finally able to observe the presence of oxygen atoms in Venus’ upper atmosphere.
The presence of atomic oxygen is quite significant because it’s a key component of Venus’ atmospheric loss rate, or how fast the planet’s atmosphere is leaving Venus and going out into space. The presence of oxygen means the planet is losing some amount of its atmosphere, and as such, will lose some of its atmosphere to space. It also suggests that Venus may have had a significant atmosphere in the past, but that it has now been reduced to what we see today.

In 2023, Walt Hearn is vice president of worldwide sales and customer excellence at Ansys. Hearn: Engineering teams know the design cycle well: Start with last year’s model, make it a little more efficient. Then, with new technology, you can make it even better. For many, that’s all that matters. But there’s something missing in that equation.
You see, engineering teams often work in a vacuum. Design teams don’t see the entire process from start to finish. They’re not connected to all the teams downstream. And there are often multiple teams involved in each project, so they’re not connected to the teams upstream.
That’s where the “missing piece” comes in. The missing piece is the customer. Customers have a very clear idea of what they want. That’s not always what engineers have in mind. Engineers know that efficiency is key, but customers know that they want to use less of it.
The customer’s perspective is crucial to understanding what they want and how to make their lives easier. And it’s also important for them to understand how their needs will impact the entire process.
The missing piece is also important for engineers because they need to understand how their work affects other teams

In 2023, The term holistic admissions is heard a lot in this age of test-optional college admissions. 70% of admissions officers say that a student’s personal qualities are an important factor in their review of applicants. If you’re not sure what holistic admissions are, this blog will explain.
Holistic Admissions Definition
Holistic admissions is a college admissions practice in which each applicant is considered as an individual rather than as a part of a class or a statistic. The holistic approach considers a variety of factors that are not quantifiable, such as an applicant’s personality, cultural context, and community involvement, among others. The holistic approach to college admissions is a shift away from the traditional use of quantitative factors such as test scores and GPA to determine admission decisions.
What is Holistic Admissions Example

In 2023, Sodium has the potential to make inroads into energy storage and electric vehicles because it’s cheaper and far more abundant than lithium. While chemically and structurally similar, sodium has yet to be used on a large scale. That could be about to change. “The world will run out of lithium by 2030, and if you want to build a battery with enough capacity to replace oil and gas, you’ll need sodium,” said John Blystone, founder and CEO of Sila Nanotechnologies, which makes anode material for sodium-ion batteries.
While lithium is an excellent battery material, the element is scarce and costly, meaning sodium is likely to become a key part of the energy storage mix. As the world shifts to electrification, it will need to find cheaper, more abundant materials to make the batteries that will store the energy from wind turbines and solar panels. Lithium-ion batteries are still the workhorses for electric vehicles, and sodium-ion batteries haven’t even scratched the surface of their potential. Yet, despite that fact, the world could see a surge in demand for these batteries, as electric vehicles are set to become more popular in the coming years.

The double burden of dwindling availability - and inadequate water for drinking and sanitation services - is compounding the challenge. As temperatures rise and demand for water grows, the future of access to water is uncertain. Here is why:
High temperatures increase the rate at which water evaporates from lakes, rivers and reservoirs. This, in turn, reduces water levels. Higher temperatures also increase the evaporation rate of water used in agriculture, leading to more runoff and less water available for drinking and sanitation. As a result, water availability is decreasing in many parts of the world.
The double burden of high temperatures and inadequate water infrastructure is creating water stress. Water stress refers to the limited availability of water resources to meet the demands of society, agriculture, and the environment.
The World Health Organization defines water stress as the ratio of available water resources to demand. Water stress is measured using the Water Stress Index (WSI), which compares the amount of water available for consumption and the amount of water consumed.

In 2023, Cholera is an acute diarrhoeal infection caused by consuming food or water contaminated with the bacterium vibrio cholerae. Back in 2008-2009 more than 4,000 went to their graves when the water-borne infection spread. At the height of the epidemic, more than 50 people were being diagnosed with cholera every day.
A group of patients with cholera were taken to a private hospital. They were given the wrong medication for the infection and as a result, the infection spread to other parts of the country and the number of cases increased by 3,000.
According to medical specialists, the cause of the cholera outbreak was the use of contaminated water in the treatment of Covid-19.
It is possible to prevent cholera with proper hygiene.
In order to protect yourself and your family from cholera, you should always follow proper hygiene. You should drink water and boil it before using it for drinking. You should also wash your hands properly before eating, preparing food, and cleaning.
You should always use clean and clean water for washing, bathing, and cooking. If possible, you should use boiled water.

In 2023, agora series, a hybrid film-series industry strand, returns this year for its sophomore outing. This year’s agora series program will run for two extended days, starting november 4. It will be open to the public and free of charge.
In 2022, agora series became a platform for industry discussions around topics related to film production and distribution. This year, agora series will focus on issues around film finance, distribution, and talent management, as well as the film industry’s response to geopolitical and societal changes in the current socio-political climate.
agora series is organized by the european film promotion and the polish film institute. This year’s agora series partners are the european audiovisual observatory and the european documentary network. The agora series will also host an international pitching platform and a market for industry professionals. The pitching platform is the main element of agora series this year, allowing 8 film projects from the european film industry to be pitched to European distributors and funders.
agora series 2023’s pitch competition will be hosted by the european audiovisual observatory and will feature projects from the european film industry. Projects selected to pitch are from different genres and stages of development

In 2023, The US House of Representatives on Friday began publishing more than 44,000 hours of video from the January 6, 2021 riot at the US Capitol. Thousands of supporters of then-President Donald Trump had gathered in Washington as both chambers of Congress met to certify the 2020 election for his Democrat challenger Joe Biden. As Congress convened to count the votes, the mob stormed the Capitol and delayed the vote. Five people died during the attack, and more than 140 officers were injured. The House Committee on the January 6th Attack held hearings earlier this year.
The House is also making the video publicly available online, allowing anyone to download or stream the footage and use it for noncommercial purposes. House Speaker Kevin McCarthy had previously said that he would release the footage of the attack on the US Capitol. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi had also previously requested that the House committee make the video available to the public. The House also released the full audio of the attack and the events leading up to it.

In 2023, SpaceX's giant Starship rocket successfully lifted off around 8:03 a.m. ET. The Starship successfully separated from its first-stage booster as planned. But minutes later, the cheers subsided as mission control appeared to lose contact with the vehicle. There was no further word from the vehicle for around 10 minutes. After the Starship was declared lost, Elon Musk tweeted that the rocket had "exited the atmosphere" and that the booster would be "falling through the atmosphere for an unknown period of time."
"Starship SN15 is now entering the Earth's atmosphere and will be destroyed during this descent," Musk wrote on Twitter. "Will provide an update if we get telemetry from it."
Later, Musk tweeted, "The first stage is currently falling through the atmosphere. It will be destroyed during re-entry. All 4 engines cut off. No telemetry after re-entry. We were not expecting it to survive the landing." Musk confirmed that the prototype was in a stable orbit after reaching the atmosphere, but the rocket crashed.
